Deep Generative Models for Novel GPCR Ligand Discovery

Dr. Mark James Thompson1 (thok@zhaw.ch), Dr. Manuel Dömer (supervisor)2, Dr. Tomek Stepniewski (co-supervisor)3
  1. Institute for Wealth and Asset Management, ZHAW
  2. Programme Director BSc. Data Science, ZHAW
  3. Senior Scientist Computational Chemistry, InterAx AG

Generative AI can help find new drugs to combat multiple sclerosis.

A conditional-RNN helps find novel inverse agonist ligands for ACKR3, a GPCR involved in MS pathology

Abstract

ACKR3 is an atypical chemokine receptor that is involved in various pathologies. Identifying a viable inverse agonists would help to combat pathologies like multiple sclerosis (Pouzol 2022). Inhibiting ACKR3 has been shown to be possible (Bosma 2012).

In this project, we use a conditional recurrent neural network models to generate novel ligands that may bind, and hopefully turn off that receptor.

Methods

  1. Gather relevant molecules:
  • ZINC clinical
  • ChEMBL GPCR ligands
  • GLASS ACKR3 ligands
  • InterAx ACKR3 ligands

  1. Use gnina to predict ACKR3 binding scores of molecules

  2. Integrate the molecules (SMILES) and scores with KNIME;

  3. Develop an RNN for SMILES using:

    • 3 LSTM layers
    • 20% dropout
    • conditioning on binding score
    • 512 nodes
    • optimizing w/ sparse-cross entropy

  4. Simulate the ligands in Boltz-2.

Implementation

After months of scoring 90’000 docked ligands, we finally had a working dataset for our conditional RNN model. Several RNN models from the literature were extended as conditional models, and tested. We generated

Evaluation

Is there a best RNN model that works with conditioning in our experimental setup? Yes, but its not clear because of different training datasets.

We ran a comparison of RNN models experiments with different amounts of nodes and layers. We found that complicated models, like the 3 layer dropout model is not necessarily better than simpler architectures.

Results

In conclusion, in our research we show:

  • gnina can predict binding that accords with empirical assays;
  • Conditioning on a binding score is useful for enriching an RNN;
  • Boltz-2 is becoming a possible substitute for MD.

A conditional generative RNN is a useful model for the generating molecules. Our framework for developing novel molecules is relatively simple and can applied to other parameters or ligands.

Extra Tables & Figures

gnina can predict

Figure 1: KNIME reports a modest but statistcaly significant correlation of 0.236 between gnina binding score the binding affinity as measure interms of pChEMBL (p-value=0.000 on 575 degrees of freedom)

Bigger isn’t Better

The Segler model has many more hidden nodes (1024) and complicated structure (3-layers), but even smaller models with 512 nodes can generate similar results. Bigger is not necessarily better when it comes to conditional RNN models.
